00:41.409 --> 00:42.909
Good morning, people.

00:42.944 --> 00:45.111
Welcome to the third day of the sixth month

00:45.146 --> 00:47.447
of the year 03 A.Z.

00:47.482 --> 00:49.683
If you're listening to this,
it means you're still alive.

00:49.717 --> 00:51.785
So congratulations.

00:51.819 --> 00:53.320
Or condolences.

00:53.354 --> 00:55.155
You know, whatever.

00:55.456 --> 00:59.059
If you're noticing more despair
in my voice than usual today,

00:59.093 --> 01:01.728
it's because we lost someone special.

01:01.762 --> 01:05.197
I know, we lose people all the time.

01:05.233 --> 01:07.534
Getting your face chewed
off by a Z is more common

01:07.568 --> 01:09.736
than making it to your next birthday.

01:09.770 --> 01:11.505
But this guy...

01:13.274 --> 01:15.509
This one's worth mentioning.

01:15.543 --> 01:19.713
Charles Garnett, First Sergeant,
Army National Guard Reservist,

01:19.747 --> 01:24.484
was an honest to God,
real life, actual good guy.

01:24.519 --> 01:27.954
He fought for other people,
not just for his own survival.

01:27.989 --> 01:30.357
And he did something that's
pretty much impossible

01:30.391 --> 01:31.758
these days.

01:31.792 --> 01:33.493
He gave people hope.

01:34.996 --> 01:37.030
Remember hope?

01:37.064 --> 01:39.065
Remember thinking that we might actually

01:39.100 --> 01:41.434
come out on the other side of this thing?

01:41.469 --> 01:43.370
Yeah. That.

01:43.404 --> 01:47.874
Sergeant Garnett died trying
to give us a reason to hope.

01:48.576 --> 01:50.744
And for that...

01:54.148 --> 01:56.683
Sergeant Charles Garnett.

01:56.717 --> 01:59.386
On behalf of a grateful nation,

01:59.420 --> 02:01.855
or whatever the hell we are now,

02:02.823 --> 02:04.858
we salute you.

02:36.924 --> 02:37.757
Radiator?

02:37.792 --> 02:39.559
Yeah.

02:39.594 --> 02:40.560
Fixable?

02:40.595 --> 02:41.962
Don't know.

02:41.996 --> 02:44.297
Gee, if we only had a mechanic.

02:44.332 --> 02:45.932
You got to let her deal, man.

02:45.967 --> 02:47.634
She's got that post-traumatic stress.

02:47.668 --> 02:49.603
She's got post-traumatic stress?

02:49.637 --> 02:52.806
The whole world's got post-traumatic stress.

02:52.840 --> 02:54.841
Actually there isn't anything post about it.

02:54.875 --> 02:57.077
We all got plain ol' present tense,

02:57.111 --> 02:59.613
all traumatic, all stress all the time.

02:59.814 --> 03:01.982
What makes her so special?

03:03.417 --> 03:06.453
Hey. Wake up. Hey.

03:08.022 --> 03:10.924
No, you can't just check out.

03:11.292 --> 03:12.926
We got a job to do.

03:19.700 --> 03:21.601
And I am running out of time.

03:21.636 --> 03:24.304
And California is still
2,000 miles of bad road away.

03:24.338 --> 03:26.873
And we are <i> not</i> gonna make it without you.

03:27.475 --> 03:29.643
Cuz it's not like they're gonna follow me

03:29.677 --> 03:32.212
or the old man or the
wonder twins out there.

03:32.246 --> 03:34.047
Hey.

03:46.394 --> 03:49.029
All right, Addy and I will scout up ahead.

03:49.063 --> 03:50.630
See if we can get some help.

03:50.665 --> 03:51.698
We will?

03:51.732 --> 03:53.566
Yeah.

03:53.601 --> 03:56.636
Yeah, I dunno, guys.
I think we should stick together.

03:56.671 --> 03:57.904
No, Doc. Don't worry.

03:57.938 --> 03:59.873
We're just gonna scout ahead and
circle back around and find you.

03:59.907 --> 04:01.775
I mean it's not like you're
getting far in the truck.

04:01.809 --> 04:02.742
Come on, Addy.

04:08.382 --> 04:10.250
I can't believe I'm saying this, but

04:10.284 --> 04:12.919
what if Warren doesn't snap out of it?

04:13.554 --> 04:15.722
She's not giving up.

04:16.223 --> 04:17.290
All right, well

04:17.324 --> 04:19.759
we can't just sit here
and wait for help to come.

04:19.793 --> 04:21.728
I mean we got to do something.

04:21.762 --> 04:23.930
Okay.

04:33.174 --> 04:35.942
I found the leak in the radiator hose.

04:35.976 --> 04:37.644
Taped it up a little bit, but

04:37.678 --> 04:41.347
we're not going anywhere unless
we get some water in there.

04:49.657 --> 04:50.757
I get thirsty.

04:50.791 --> 04:53.359
We all get thirsty.

04:57.798 --> 04:59.232
I'll drive.

04:59.266 --> 05:01.434
Knock yourself out, kid.

05:05.806 --> 05:06.673
Whoa! Whoa!

05:06.707 --> 05:08.975
Easy there, kid! Easy!

05:09.009 --> 05:10.844
Who taught you how to drive?

05:10.878 --> 05:11.911
Ahhh...

05:11.946 --> 05:13.313
no one.

05:14.415 --> 05:16.783
Hands on the ten and the two.

05:18.085 --> 05:20.587
And easy on the gas.

05:50.985 --> 05:52.819
Nothin' out here.

05:52.853 --> 05:55.922
No people, no gas, not even Zs.

05:56.056 --> 05:58.424
Nah, we got to go back.

05:58.993 --> 06:00.360
There is no help out here.

06:00.394 --> 06:02.796
There's no help back there either.

06:04.732 --> 06:07.133
We have to go back, Mack.

06:07.868 --> 06:09.435
We have a mission.

06:09.470 --> 06:11.037
We made a promise.

06:11.071 --> 06:12.772
No, we didn't.

06:12.807 --> 06:14.007
We never did.

06:14.041 --> 06:16.543
Addy, the only promise we
ever made was to each other.

06:16.577 --> 06:18.111
To stay alive.

06:18.145 --> 06:19.412
Look, yeah, okay.

06:19.446 --> 06:23.550
Maybe we didn't say the words
and we didn't sign an oath. But

06:24.084 --> 06:25.518
we all stand for each other.

06:25.553 --> 06:27.120
We don't leave each other behind.

06:27.154 --> 06:29.722
Garnett came back for me when
those cannibals kidnapped me.

06:29.757 --> 06:31.891
And now you want to leave Warren?

06:33.727 --> 06:35.595
She needs us.

06:35.629 --> 06:37.997
They all need us.

06:38.032 --> 06:39.766
I just think

06:40.768 --> 06:43.803
maybe we have a better chance on our own.

06:43.838 --> 06:46.239
Like in the beginning.

06:46.273 --> 06:48.208
Mmm-hmmm.

06:49.743 --> 06:51.344
So how long?

06:52.646 --> 06:53.513
What?

06:54.682 --> 06:56.282
How long before you think
that you have a better chance

06:56.317 --> 06:57.884
on your own?

06:59.653 --> 07:01.387
Addy. Whoa.

07:01.422 --> 07:02.956
Hey.

07:02.990 --> 07:05.225
I came back for you.

07:05.259 --> 07:05.758
Hmmm?

07:05.793 --> 07:07.660
The cannibals.

07:07.695 --> 07:11.598
I came back for you.
I'll always come back for you.

07:16.403 --> 07:18.771
You know me.

07:19.640 --> 07:21.774
I'm not so sure anymore.

07:21.809 --> 07:23.877
About anything.

07:24.879 --> 07:25.945
All right.

07:28.682 --> 07:29.883
We'll go back.

07:33.420 --> 07:34.854
Okay.

07:40.628 --> 07:41.961
Go right.

07:42.296 --> 07:43.329
Why right?

07:43.697 --> 07:45.732
Why not?

07:52.706 --> 07:53.606
No Zs.

07:53.641 --> 07:55.375
That's a good sign.

07:58.445 --> 08:00.413
Getting interesting.

08:01.949 --> 08:04.918
Liquor! Now you're talking.

08:04.952 --> 08:07.420
Murphy, we're gonna have to
let you navigate more often.

08:08.555 --> 08:11.557
Congratulations, son.
You're now the designated driver.

08:11.592 --> 08:13.092
What's that mean?

08:13.460 --> 08:14.761
It means step on it!

08:38.919 --> 08:42.188
I've never
seen so many in one place.

08:42.222 --> 08:44.157
So much for going back.

08:49.930 --> 08:51.698
<i> ♪ Have mercy... ♪</i>

08:53.701 --> 08:57.531
<i> ♪ Oh, have mercy. ♪</i>

08:57.631 --> 08:59.555
